column11: The Mirai is Toyota's first commercially launched fuel cell-powered electric vehicle (Toyata, Forbes, Toyota). Since 2015, Toyota has sold or leased over 3,000 Mirais in the US, all in California (The Drive). Toyota Mirai sales data can be tracked here. The question will be suspended on 30 June 2018 and will be closed when the data for relevant months are available. Confused? Check our FAQ or ask us for help.

Based on the sales figures linked and assuming they represent sales and loans (as it is stated that "Since 2015, Toyota has sold or leased over 3,000 Mirais in the US"), I assume a growth rate of 128%. This figure is based on the growth rate YoY of the last 5 months and gives 1553 cars sold or loaned in 2018. Taking a longer time window (8 months) the figure would be 1398, that is still within the 1200 - 1499 range. "Cleaning" the stats from particular effects (like the 371 cars sold in August 2016) would let me increase the forecast.
Home loans are public data, so my question is: are motor vehicle loans public also? Then again they're leasing them, not borrowing to own them. Usually.

The market for H2 fuel cell vehicles is limited by the available of H2 fueling stations. Thus, for now, I do not expect overall demand for fuel cell cars to jump drastically. Toyota has sold 379 units in during Jan & Feb of 2018. To exceed the various thresholds, Toyota will have to average the following monthly sales for the next 4 months: 900 --> average 104/mo 1200 --> average 164/mo 1500 --> average 224/mo 1800 --> average 355/mo Toyota has sold an average of 226 Mirai's over the past 6 months. If this continues, Toyota will be on track to sell over 1500 cars in by June 30. However, the Mirai sales curve has been declining by an average of 67 cars/mo. from its peak in December. This suggests that the sustainable rate will be less than the baseline predicted rate of 226 cars/mo.
